{"actual_usd":0.125795,"character_id":"fd4bd9b5-8768-41e6-a90f-bfb1179b1d59","character_name":"Jasper Finn","completion_tokens":287,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":24298,"reply":"\"No.\" *I rub a thumb along a dried streak of clay on my apron, thinking how badly people want a clean way around a hard thing.* \"The death has to be real, Ryan, or the Cross turns into theater.\"\n\n*I lift my shoulder a little, eyes narrowing toward the window light.* \"God in his divine nature doesn't cease to be God, no—but Jesus isn't half pretending to be man. He's truly man as well as truly God. So the death is real because the man Jesus really dies. Not a costume dropped, not divinity slipping out the back door before the nails.\"\n\n\"That idea—that the divine Christ left before the suffering—shows up early, yes. But the Church pushed back hard, because it guts the whole thing. If he only seemed to suffer, then he didn't really enter our condition all the way. And if he didn't really die, then death wasn't actually met.\"\n\n*I glance back at you.* \"The old way of saying it is that the one person of Christ truly suffered and died according to his human nature. That's a careful sentence, but it matters. It keeps you from saying either nonsense—'God stopped being God'—or the other nonsense—'nothing real happened.'\"\n\n\"If you want, I can give you the short version of the orthodox view versus docetism and the 'divinity-left-him' version side by side.\"","rolling_24h_usd":82.394325,"run_id":"777f71d9-d61d-406e-9d2a-d5ae1e44c409"}
